title: Russia deploys 100,000 troops to capture Ukraine's Pokrovsk city | The World | ABC NEWS
description: Intense fighting is continuing in and around the city of Pokrovsk in eastern Ukraine's Donetsk region, with Moscow deploying around 100,000 troops into battle in a bid to capture the strategic centre. Pokrovsk is considered a key logistics hub and military supply route in eastern Ukraine, and Russia has long seen it as a vital gateway to taking the rest of the Donetsk region. The Ukrainian army said its units were battling hard to try to stop the Russians from gaining new ground, but has acknowledged that its troops face a difficult fight. title: Building up, not out is key to solving housing supply crisis, says Grattan Institute | The Business
description: Australia needs around 250,000 new homes to be built a year over the next four years to reach the 1.2 million home government target. 176,000 homes were built in the first year of the National Housing Accord. Builders and experts agree building out isn't enough. Now the prominent think-tank The Grattan Institute says building up is part of the solution. Housing and economic security programme director at the Grattan Institute, Brendan Coates says Australian cities are some of the least dense of their size in the world. "We haven't allowed enough housing in those areas where Australians most want to live in those inner and middle ring suburbs of our capital cities," he says. Grattan wants a green light for three story dwellings on every residential block, adding 67,000 new homes a year and saving $100,000 a house. However the building industry says there's a drastic short fall of skilled labour. Supervisor at McDonald Jones Homes, Brian Skinner says "Skilled labour is still the number one issue that the building industry, not only in New South Wales but across Australia, needs to tackle." Land prices have also been flagged as a barrier to building more homes. #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Former US vice-president Dick Cheney dies at 84 | ABC NEWS
description: Former US vice-president Dick Cheney has died from complications of pneumonia and cardiovascular disease at age 84.  He was widely credited as the architect of the Gulf War under president George H W Bush and the driving force behind the US invasion of Iraq under the George W Bush administration.  The former Republican politician was also known for transforming the role of US vice-president into one of power overseeing foreign policy and national security after the September 11 terror attacks.  In his late years, he was a vocal opponent of US President Donald Trump and publicly declared his vote for Democratic candidate Kamala Harris. title: Why any rate relief for borrowers is now well into next year | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: A Melbourne Cup rate cut from the Reserve Bank was a non-starter. After three cuts this year, the RBA board kept the cash rate on hold at 3.6 per cent with its Governor Michele Bullock citing hotter-than-expected inflation. The RBA now says it's on the fence when it comes to its next interest rate move.  But some economists say any rate relief for borrowers won't happen until at least the middle of 2026. Economist Chris Richardson says "the last mile in the fight against inflation is pretty tough" for most central banks. Cost of living pressures are being driven by surging electricity prices and housing, with property prices rising at the fastest pace in more than two years. For borrowers, Canstar's Sally Tindall says there's been a surge in refinancing -- with roughly a thousand borrowers switching lenders each day. Ms Tindall says the average owner occupier's variable is around 5.5 per cent, but a competitive rate would be below 5.25 per cent. #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Is the government's plan to give free power not as good as it seems? | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: From July next year, households will have access to at least three free hours of power as long as they take up the default market offer and have a smart meter. The government's newly announced Solar Sharer Scheme will force retailers to make it available to consumers in NSW, South East Queensland, and South Australia. The aim is to soak up the nation's abundant daytime solar power, stabilising the grid and lowering power prices in peak periods. The founder of SolarQuotes, now owned by Origin Energy, Finn Peacock says its a great headline, but the devil is in the detail. " I think its a good idea to reduce the cost of electricity during the day, to encourage more electricity during the day, but I think forcing retailers to offer it for free for three hours is only likely to push up other costs for consumers." Power retailers say they've been blindsided and shocked by the scheme that puts smaller operators under pressure. Chief Executive Officer at the Australian Energy Council says "Generally the charge that comes from the companies that operate the poles are wires still exists for that middle of the day but retailers are effectively covering that cost in the middle of the day." she says " For smaller retailers in particular we do need to think carefully about whether they can actually cover those costs. "   #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: ACT voluntary assisted dying scheme begins, allowing Canberrans to 'die with dignity' | ABC NEWS
description: Warning: The following video contains content that viewers may find distressing.  November 3 marks the beginning of the ACT's voluntary assisted dying scheme, making the territory the second-last Australian jurisdiction to legalise it.   For Canberran Gail Ford, it's about "choice" and "dignity".   Over the more than 20 years that Gail has lived with Parkinson's disease, it has steadily and determinedly stripped away her abilities, and her independence.  For those reasons and more, Gail wants the option of voluntary assisted dying. title: Will the Liberals follow the Nationals in dumping net zero commitment? | ABC NEWS
description: The Nationals have formally announced the party is ditching its commitment to net zero emissions by 2050, and instead will focus on climate adaptation. title: UK Train Knife Attack Not Being Treated As Terrorist Incident | 10 News
description: UK Police have confirmed that a knife attack on a London-bound train that left 11 in hospital, is not being treated as a terrorist incident.  Police immediately arrested two men following the attack at Huntingdon Train Station, both of whom were British nationals, before releasing one without charge.  A 32-year-old man remains under arrest and is being questioned on suspicion of attempted murder.  Six victims remain in hospital, with one in a life-threatening condition. title: Teens Arrested Following Clash With D.C. Police On Halloween | 10 News
description: At least five teenagers were arrested after a violent clash with D.C.‚Äôs Metropolitan Police Department (MPD) on Friday night.  According to the Metropolitan Police Department, the arrests were made for ‚Äúdisorderly behaviour‚Äù on Halloween evening, with additional arrests carried out by Metro Transit Police.  Police reported that a crowd of about 700 people had gathered around 8pm, in a park area near downtown‚Äôs Navy Yard Metro station. description: Prince Andrew. War hero, Queen Elizabeth's favourite son, the Duke of York. Born into a life of privilege and duty, destined to serve the Crown as a senior member of the Royal Family. But the gilded life masked a very different one in private. A shadow loomed, cast by the Prince's relationship with Jeffrey Epstein. The world watched as a disastrous television interview turned scandal into catastrophe. It was the beginning of the end for Andrew. It set in motion his downfall. His titles stripped. His reputation.. in ruins.  For the first time in generations, a British Prince has been banished. This is a detailed documentary timeline of how the King's brother lost everything. The extraordinary story of Prince Andrew, Duke of York, whose life of privilege and duty unravelled due to his association with convicted sex offender Jeffrey Epstein and the sexual assault allegations by Virginia Giuffre.  This video traces the complete timeline of the scandal, from the initial connections and the explosive 2019 BBC Newsnight interview, through the civil lawsuit, the removal of his military titles, and the final, historic move by King Charles to strip his brother of all remaining royal styles, titles, and honours. It details the public outrage, the "Pizza Express" alibi, the multi-million-dollar out-of-court settlement, and his ultimate exile from public life. title: US Ambassador interrupted by Cuba at UN | ABC NEWS
description: US Ambassador to the UN Mike Waltz was interrupted during a speech at the United Nations General Assembly by the Foreign Minister of Cuba, Bruno Rodriguez.   The General Assembly were due to vote on whether to condemn the United States' economic restrictions on Cuba.   "Mr Waltz, this is the United Nations General Assembly," Mr Rodriguez said. "It's not a Signal chat. Nor is it the House of Representatives."   He also said Mr Waltz was speaking in an "uncivilised, crude and gross way".  But Mr Waltz's speech was unable to convince many countries, with the UN General Assembly voting 165-7, with 12 abstentions to condemn the US economic embargo against Cuba. title: Victorian parliament passes Indigenous treaty

title: New AFP taskforce to target men 'hunting' young girls for violent acts | ABC NEWS
description: The Australian Federal Police have been working with Microsoft to develop AI tools to interpret Gen Z and Alpha slang to quickly identify children at risk of sadistic online exploitation.  New AFP Commissioner Krissy Barrett used her first speech at the National Press Club on Wednesday to announce the creation of Taskforce Pompilid, which will use the technology amongst a raft of measures to crack down on decentralised online crime networks.    The AFP is warning that young girls are being "hunted, stalked and drawn-in" by men using online networks to coerce them into carrying out serious acts of violence on themselves, their siblings or pets, in a "twisted type of gamification".  The Commissioner also offered practical steps to keep children out of harm's way.  "Let kids know they have the right to feel safe online and, if something feels uncomfortable, they can leave a chat at any time and tell a safe adult.   You can encourage safe conversations by talking regularly about online activities and apps, encouraging critical thinking, and reassuring kids that they won't be punished for coming forward if they think they have done something wrong.   Also, you can look out for warning signs that include self-harm, changes in eating or sleeping habits, sudden withdrawal from friends, families or activities, use of extreme behaviour, extreme language or symbols, and rejection of previously held morals.   Importantly, there are really practical and easy resources available, including how to make a report about child exploitation, at the AFP-led Australian Centre to Counter Child Exploitation website. That's www.acce.gov.au". she said.  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. The failure affected a wide range of cloud-based websites and services including Microsoft Office 365, Heathrow Airport, Alaska and Hawaiian Airlines, as well as XBox and Minecraft. It's the second outage involving a cloud computing service in a week. Issues with Amazon's AWS platform took down a broad range of online services, including social media, gaming, food delivery, streaming and financial platforms. title: Helicopter Crashes Near Everest Base Camp | 10 News
description: A private helicopter sent to rescue stranded trekkers crashed while attempting to land at Lobuche near Everest Base Camp on Wednesday.  Officials said the aircraft slipped on snow during landing and came to rest on its side.  The pilot survived and was later rescued; it is unknown whether the trekkers have been rescued.  The crash came as heavy snow and cyclone winds forced authorities to close both the Nepali and Chinese sides of the Everest region to trekkers.  Trekking routes across Annapurna, Manaslu and Dhaulagiri have also been halted amid days of severe weather and dangerous trail conditions. title: Jamaica Declared Disaster Zone As Hurricane Melissa Rips Through Cuba | 10 News
description: The devastation of Hurricane Melissa on Jamaica has become clearer, as the nation is declared as a disaster zone while the storm moves on to Cuba.  Melissa has been declared Jamaica's strongest ever storm on record, with four people confirmed dead in the country, while dozens have been killed in Haiti.  Eyewitness accounts show the flooding in Cuba's Holguin Province following Melissa's passage through the region.  Hundreds of Cuban rural communities have been isolated, while the city of Santiago was also heavily hit. title: Australian faces lengthy US jail term after selling trade secrets to Russian broker | ABC NEWS
description: An Australian man has pleaded guilty in a Washington DC court to selling cybersecurity information to a Russian broker.  Peter Williams admitted to leaking eight trade secrets from his company, which is a subcontractor for the US Department of Defense, to a company which sells cyber exploit opportunities to the Kremlin.  The 39-year-old former Australian Signals Directorate (ASD) employee is now facing up to 20 years in jail. US Attorney-General Pam Bondi says the case signals that American national security is ‚Äònot for sale‚Äô. title: Anti-ICE protests erupt in LA as Federal agents conduct pre-dawn raid
description: An anti-ICE activist in Los Angeles has been apprehended by federal authorities in a pre-dawn Los Angeles raid. Nine other suspects were also arrested for allegedly attacking law enforcement officers during immigration enforcement operations. title: No rate cut until mid-2026, says NAB chief economist | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: Inflation has surged in the September quarter with consumer prices rising at an annual pace of 3.2 per cent, up from 2.1 per cent in the June quarter. The "trimmed mean" for the September quarter, which strips out the most volatile price moves up and down, came in at 1 per cent. The headline number was 1.3 per cent. On an annual basis, the trimmed mean lifted to the top of the RBA's target band at 3 per cent. It was much hotter than the RBA and market economists were expecting, squashing hopes of a rate cut next week. In fact, NAB chief economist Sally Auld told The Business NAB isn't expecting another rate cut until mid-2026. "No rate cuts for the rest of this year, likely no rate cuts in the first quarter of next year, but we do have one more rate cut in our profile but not until May of 2026," She said. "I think really the message from today's numbers is that it is going to require a little bit of patience on the part of mortgage holders just to give the Reserve Bank a good chance to get comfortable and a bit more confident in terms of some of the underlying drivers of inflation."  #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE Read more here: https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-10-29/september-quarter-inflation-kills-interest-rate-cut/105946770  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: King Charles heckled over brother Prince Andrew | ABC NEWS
description: King Charles was heckled by a protester on Monday over his brother Prince Andrew's ties to the late sex offender Jeffrey Epstein. The king was greeting royal fans during a cathedral visit in Britain.  "How long have you known about Andrew and Epstein?," the man could be heard shouting outside Lichfield Cathedral in northwest England, close to Birmingham.  Although Prince Andrew, 65, said this month that he would give up using his title of Duke of York after years of scrutiny over his behaviour and connections to Epstein, questions about him ‚Äî and what the royals knew of events ‚Äî have intensified since.  The contents of a posthumous memoir by Virginia Giuffre, who accused the prince of sexually abusing her as a teenager, have triggered renewed backlash over the issue this month.  Andrew has always denied Giuffre's account. In 2022, he made an undisclosed payment to settle a lawsuit brought in the US by Giuffre, who died by suicide in April.  British police are looking into media reports that in 2011 Andrew had asked one of his police officers to dig up dirt on Giuffre.  The protester could also be heard saying: "Have you asked the police to cover up for Andrew? ... Should the MPs (members of parliament) be allowed to debate the royals in the House of Commons?"  The monarch ignored the protester and carried on engaging with other members of the public.  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Donald Trump says he 'would love' third term | ABC NEWS
description: US President Donald Trump ruled out running for the vice presidency in the 2028 election, an approach some of his supporters have floated to allow the Republican president to serve an additional term in office. The remarks were Trump's latest on the subject, which he has teased in public remarks and with "Trump 2028" hats he hands out at the White House. No one may be elected to the US presidency a third time, according to the 22nd Amendment of the US Constitution. Some have suggested that one way around this prohibition would be for Trump to stand as vice president, while another candidate stood for president and resigned, letting Trump again assume the presidency. Opponents have disputed whether this would be legal. Referring to Vice President JD Vance and Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Trump also said they were "great people" who could run for the office. description: US President Donald Trump has once again refused to categorically rule out attempting to run for a third presidential term, further stoking rising fears he may try to subvert the US constitution.  The constitution's 22nd amendment prevents anyone from being elected to the office of president more than twice. However, this hasn't stopped rampant speculation that Trump will mount a move to either remain in office in 2028, or find a legal workaround to permit a third tilt at the presidency.  Speaking aboard Air Force One, Trump was asked point-blank if he would rule out a third run. "Am I ruling it out? You tell me," he responded. Trump did, however, address one popularly held theory that he could run as Vice President behind JD Vance, with Vance immediately stepping down after winning an election. Despite that too being constitutionally forbidden, Trump said he would not do it because "it's too cute." title: Putin touts the potential of ‚Äòinvincible‚Äô nuclear-capable cruise missile
description: Russian President Vladimir Putin has boasted about the capability of Russia's "invincible" nuclear-capable cruise missile.  The Burevestnik missile, or known by its NATO code-name as "Skyfall", was successfully tested on Sunday, said Putin.  The Russian president appeared in military fatigues to tout the success of his new missile.  During the address, Putin called on his top generals to begin preparing missiles for potential use.  "We need to determine the possible uses and begin preparing the infrastructure for deploying these weapons to our armed forces", Putin said.  Previously, Putin said the weapon is capable of bypassing missile defence systems and has an almost infinite range.  Moscow has boasted of the missile's capability, but it remains unclear if the Burevestnik missile can do what Putin says it can.

title: JD Vance unleashes on Zohran Mamdani over 9/11 comment in online roast
description: US Vice President JD Vance has savagely roasted New York City Democrat Mayoral candidate Zohran Mamdani.  In a post to social media, Vance brutally responded to a comment Mamdani had made about 9/11.  While speaking in New York City in the Bronx, Mamdani delivered an address on Islamophobia, where he brought up a story about his family's experience with 9/11. title: Trump heads to Japan after inking deals with ASEAN nations | ABC NEWS
description: US President Donald Trump is headed to Japan after signing a swathe of trade deals with South East Asian nations at the ASEAN summit.  The agreements will allow these countries to keep US tariffs on their exports at the current rates in exchange for buying more US products including Boeing planes.  The US leader also witnessed the official signing ceremony of a Thailand-Cambodia peace treaty alongside Malaysian Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim in Kuala Lumpur.  Mr Trump is scheduled to meet with newly-appointed Japanese Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi before attending the APEC Summit in South Korea.  Meanwhile, US Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent and Chinese Deputy Premier He Lifeng have agreed to a framework for anticipated trade talks between President Trump and his Chinese counterpart Xi Jinping. title: Trump Slams UN, Accepts Nobel Peace Prize Nomination After Thai-Cambodia Peace Deal | 10 News
description: US President Donald Trump has claimed a peace accord between Thailand and Cambodia, while taking petty shots at the United Nations over the now-infamous teleprompter and escalator incidents.  Speaking in Kuala Lumpur following the signing of a ceasefire agreement between the two warring nations, Trump brought up how the UN "should be doing this" and that "they turned off my teleprompter when I made a speech." Trump also once again claimed the United States was the "hottest country anywhere in the world," and that ending wars was something "much more serious than a hobby" for him.  Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Manet glowingly thanked President Trump for his role in brokering the ceasefire accord - which also came with the announcement of a rare earth minerals deal between the US and Thailand - confirming he had formally nominated Trump for the Nobel Peace Prize. title: Australian women's cricket players 'touched inappropriately' in India | ABC NEWS
description: A man has been arrested for allegedly inappropriately touching two members of Australia's Women's World Cup team in India.
